<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-17T14:56:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-17T14:56:00-05:00" n="167" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.21/277.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Thomson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Bogotá</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-17T15:00:00-04:56">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 17, 1914, 3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Apprehending that questions will arise in our Senate regarding the use
                            Colombia may make of the indemnity, the Minister for Foreign Affairs has
                            suggested the desirability of my informing you that <pb facs="0281" n="165" xml:id="pg_165"/> while he cannot speak officially for the
                            new administration, which will take office on August 7, it is the desire
                            of those in authority that the indemnity should be invested exclusively
                            in public works, especially railways and the improvement and sanitation
                            of ports, under law enacted by Congress. My own observation leads me to
                            believe that this is the wish of the thinking people as well as the
                            majority of Congress. * * *</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Thomson</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>